401","1455":"1455","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"circa 1340","Somerleyton, Suffolk, England":"Somerleyton, Suffolk, England","Depwade, Norfolk, England":"Depwade, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"about 1340–":"about 1340–Deceased","1340–1403":"1340–1403","1364–1401":"1364–1401","1340–Female":"1340–Deceased","1403":"1403","1401":"1401","1455":"1455","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"about 1340","Somerleyton, Suffolk, England":"Somerleyton, Suffolk, England","Depwade, Norfolk, England":"Depwade, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shelton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire): habitational name primarily from Shelton (Nottinghamshire), but also from Shelton (Bedfordshire, Norfolk, Shropshire, and Staffordshire). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>scelf</i> ‘rock, ledge, shelf’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Agatha","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Good, kind"],"variants":[]},{"name":"Geddney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): habitational name from a place in Lincolnshire, probably so named from an Old English personal name <i>Gǣda</i> or <i>Gydda</i> (genitive <i>-n</i>) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gidney","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is usually said to be a Norman baronial name from <i>Saint-Denis</i> in France. However, at least in the case of the family of the poet and soldier  Sir Philip Sidney  (  1554–86 ), it appears to have a more humble origin, being derived from lands in Surrey named as the ‘wide meadow’ (Old English <i>sīdan</i> ‘wide’ (dative case) + <i>ēg</i> ‘island in a river, riverside meadow’). Evidence of use as a given name dates back to the 18th century, and the popularity of the boy's name increased considerably in the 19th century, probably due in part to  Sydney Carton , hero of  Dickens's  novel A Tale of Two Cities (  1859 ). As a girl's name it arose in part as a contracted form of   Sidony ;  coincidentally it represents an altered form of   Sindy .  In recent years, the girls' name, usually written  <b>Sydney</b> , has become popular throughout the English-speaking world, especially in North America."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":115,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agatha Geddney Shelton was born about 1340, in Depwade, Norfolk, England. She had at least 1 son with John Jernegan II. She died in Somerleyton, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"about 1340–":"umbes 1340–Surnud","1340–1403":"1340–1403","1364–1401":"1364–1401","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1403":"1403","1401":"1401","1455":"1455","1364":"1364","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Somerleyton, Suffolk, England":"Somerleyton, Suffolk, England","Depwade, Norfolk, England":"Depwade, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1340–":"noin 1340–Kuollut","1340–1403":"1340–1403","1364–1401":"1364–14